      "writtenOn": "2018-12-21T02:53:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e \"trusty-10\" \u003c \"trusty-9\" \n\nYou are correct. Sorry, one would need to pad numbers with leading zeros, probably 6 digits is good enough for long foreseeable future.\n\n\u003e  why? services like Swarming are relying on them\n\nIndeed, swarming does rely on them, and whenever datastore index lags, we get weird swarming behavior (most recent happened in October). Similarly, this hit Buildbukcet at least twice, resulting in CQ not noticing builds it just scheduled, so Nodir had to make buildset search after new build inserting consistent.\n\nI\u0027m not against secondary indexes in general, my point is don\u0027t add them when not necessary. And here they aren\u0027t.\n\nAnd, composite primary keys are normal thing in scalable databases, e.g., https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/database/choosing-the-right-dynamodb-partition-key/ (secondary part called sort key there).\n\n\n\u003e GCE Backend literally does queries over 5000 entities like...\n\nyeah, i noticed :) But in this case it doesn\u0027t need to...",
